<DOC><DOCNO> ZF32-237-292 </DOCNO><DOCID>10 765 324</DOCID><JOURNAL>Electronic Engineering Times  Jan 28 1991 n626 p70(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Scan links up with design automation. (part of a continuing serieson major advances in the design-for-test field)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Waicukauski, Frank; Binnendyk, Howard Unkeles; Ferguson, Gary.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>The most widely used approach in designing testable circuits isscan design.andP;  Improvements in automation now offer designers newlevels of complexity in which scan provides a vital role throughautomation of design and test tasks.andP;  Scan design makes completeautomation of the design-to-test cycle possible and allows thecontrol of the values in all of the latches in a circuit to beobserved in a straight-forward manner.andP;  Scan is applied at eitherthe integrated circuit (IC) level or board level.andP;  The scan-pathmethod is the simplest scan-design method, IBM's LSSD methodprovides an alternative.andP;  It is important for design engineers toknow the trade-offs involved in making sequential circuits fullyscan-able.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Test EquipmentCircuit DesignScanningDesignAutomationTrends.andO;Feature:   illustrationchart.andO;Caption:   How to scan. (chart)andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>